OFDM
====
	OFDM Algorithm:
		1. Take a block of bits b(0), b(1), ... b(p-1)
		2. b(m) --> X_m = 0,1,...p-1
		3. Synthesize periodic signal x(n)=\sum_(m=0)^(p-1) X_m e^(imwn)
		4. Transmit the signal through channel
		5. Recieve y(n)
		6. Analyze y(n) to get FS coefficients Y_m s
			y(n)=\sum_(m=0)^(p-1) Y_m e^(imwn)
		7. y_m = H(mw)X_m

	Problem:
		It takes too much time to transmit a periodic signal for an infinite amount of time.

	Solution:
		Use DFT instead of DTFT

		Add Cyclic Prefix to signal block and use DTFT to generate signal

	The spacing between frequencies is W/p, where p is the number of bits per block, and W is bandwidth.

	Because of the doppler effect, it is necessary to make spacing sufficiently large (~10kHz, since most doppler shifts are ~100Hz)


CTFT
====
	periodic 
	--------
		x(t)=\sum_(m=-\infinity)^(\infinity) X_m e^(imw_0t)
		w_0, w_0=2\pi/p
	
	aperiodic:
	----------
		x(t)=1/(2\pi) \integral_(k=-infinity)^(infinity) X(\omega) e^(imw_0t) dw

		X(w)=\integral_(-infinity)^(infinity) x(t) e^(-iwt) dt

	x(t)-->X(w)
	e^(-iw_ct)x(t)-->X(w-w_c)
	x(t-T)-->X(w)e^(-iwT)
	
	So multiplication by complex exponential in the time/frequency domain corresopnds to a shift in the frequency/time domain.  



	(Qr^3/R^3)/(4 pi r^2 ep_0)
	(Qr/R^3)/(4 pi ep_0)
	(Qr)/(4 pi ep_0 R^3)

	(Qr^2)/(4 pi ep_0 R^3)

	Q/(4 pi ep_0 R)
